Package edu.uky.cs.nil.sabre.logic

Class Conjunction<E extends Expression>

java.lang.Object
edu.uky.cs.nil.sabre.logic.Conjunction<E>
Type Parameters:
E - the type of the conjunction's arguments
All Implemented Interfaces:
Expression, Logical, Proposition, Simplifiable, Typed, Countable, Serializable, Comparable<Logical>, Iterable<E>
Direct Known Subclasses:
Clause
public class Conjunction<E extends Expression> extends Object implements Iterable<E>, Countable, Proposition
A conjunction is a proposition made up of zero to many arguments (or conjuncts) which are expressions of type boolean and must all evaluate to true for the conjunction to be true.
Author:
Stephen G. Ware

      Description copied from interface: Logical
      Applies a given function to every part of this logical formula and then creates a new logical formula of this same type using the results returned from the function. If, for every part of this formula, the function always returns its input as output with no changes, this method should return this object (not just any object that is equal to this object).

    • simplify

      public Expression simplify()
      If any argument to this conjunction can be simplified to false, this method returns false. If any argument to this conjunction can be simplified to true it is removed. If there are no arguments, or if all arguments can be removed, this method returns true. If exactly one argument remains after simplification, it is returned instead of a conjunction. If two or more arguments remain, they will be put into their natural order.
      Specified by:
      simplify in interface Expression
      Specified by:
      simplify in interface Simplifiable
      Returns:
      a simplified expression, or this expression if nothing could be simplified

    • evaluate

      public Value evaluate(State state)
      Returns true if and only if every conjunct of this conjunction evaluates to true. This method is short-circuiting, which means as soon as it encounters a false conjunct, it stops evaluating its arguments and returns false.

      Specified by:

    • toEffect

      public Clause<Effect> toEffect()
      Description copied from interface: Expression
      Converts an expression whose type is boolean to disjunctive normal form (DNF) suitable to appear in the deterministic effect of an event. Because effects must be deterministic, this process must result in a disjunction of no more than one conjunctive clause whose atoms are effects. Because there will only be at most one clause, that clause is returned instead of a disjunction. If no clauses would be returned (in other words, if false would be returned), the null clause is returned.
      Specified by:
      toEffect in interface Expression
      Returns:
      a conjunctive clause whose atoms are effects
